{{Infobox book | <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Books --> | name = Heidegger: A (Very) Critical Introduction | image = File:Heidegger, A (Very) Critical Introduction.jpg | caption = Cover | authors = [[Sean McGrath (philosopher)|Sean J. McGrath]] | country = United States | language = English | subject = [[Martin Heidegger]] | publisher = [[Eerdmans]] | pub_date = 2008 | media_type = Print ([[Paperback]]) | pages = 144 pp. | isbn = 9780802860071 }}
'''''Heidegger: A (Very) Critical Introduction''''' is a 2008 book by [[Sean McGrath (philosopher)|Sean J. McGrath]], in which the author provides a [[theological]] analysis of [[Martin Heidegger]]'s thought and its relation with his political endeavors.<ref name=charlesguignon/>
==Synopsis== This book can be said to be an extension of McGrath's previous work ''[[The Early Heidegger and Medieval Philosophy]]''. McGrath argues for a clear connection between [[Heidegger’s Nazi sympathies]] and his relationship to [[Christianity]].
==Reception== ''Heidegger: A (Very) Critical Introduction'' was commissioned by the Centre for Theology and Philosophy at the [[University of Nottingham]], the theological think-tank headed by the Anglican theologian [[John Milbank]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Department of Philosophy |url=https://www.mun.ca/philosophy/people/mcgrath.php |website=[[Memorial University of Newfoundland]] |accessdate=30 September 2018 |language=en-CA}}</ref> It has been reviewed in ''Notre Dame Philosophical Reviews'', ''Dialog: A Journal of Theology'', ''[[Religious Studies Review]]'', ''[[The Heythrop Journal]]'' and ''[[Expository Times]]''.<ref name=charlesguignon>{{cite journal |last1=Guignon |first1=Charles |authorlink=Charles Guignon|title=Review of Heidegger: A (Very) Critical Introduction |journal=[[Notre Dame Philosophical Reviews]] |date=17 March 2009 |url=https://ndpr.nd.edu/news/heidegger-a-very-critical-introduction/ |accessdate=3 September 2018 |issn=1538-1617}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Mattes |first1=Mark |title=Heidegger: A (Very) Critical Introduction by S.J. McGrath |journal=Dialog |date=14 June 2010 |volume=49 |issue=2 |pages=177–178 |doi=10.1111/j.1540-6385.2010.00525.x |language=en |issn=0012-2033}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Werntz |first1=Myles |title=Heidegger: A (Very) Critical Introduction - By S. J. McGrath |journal=[[Religious Studies Review]] |date=June 2009 |volume=35 |issue=2 |pages=114 |doi=10.1111/j.1748-0922.2009.01340_5.x |language=en |issn=0319-485X}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Dillard |first1=Peter S. |title=Heidegger: A (Very) Critical Introduction. By S. J. McGrath |journal=[[The Heythrop Journal]] |date=March 2009 |volume=50 |issue=2 |pages=354–355 |doi=10.1111/j.1468-2265.2009.00460_36.x |language=en |issn=0018-1196}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Wardley |first1=Jason |title=Heidegger and Theology |journal=[[The Expository Times]] |date=11 September 2009 |volume=121 |issue=1 |pages=33 |doi=10.1177/00145246091210010602 |language=en |issn=0014-5246}}</ref> John Hughes described the book as "one of the clearest and most elegantly written [accounts of Heidegger] I have come across."<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Hughes|first1=John|title=All about being (very) critical |journal=[[Church Times]] |date=28 April 2009 |url=https://www.churchtimes.co.uk/articles/2009/1-may/books-arts/book-reviews/all-about-being-very-critical |accessdate=30 September 2018}}</ref>
